#Text=Yeğen Osman Pasha
#Text=Yeğen Osman Pasha or Yeğen Osman Aga was 17th-century Ottoman military officer of Armenian origin . [ 1 ]
#Text=After being commander of sekban ( peasant mercenaries ) units in Anatolia , he was appointed first to position of sanjakbey and serçeşme of the Sanjak of Karahisar-i Sahib .
#Text=In 1687 for a couple of months he was also the beylerbey of Rumelia Eyalet , which was the highest position he held .
#Text=Career
#Text=Reign of Mehmed IV
#Text=Yeğen Osman was commander of all Anatolian sekbans . [ 2 ]
#Text=Rivalries between the janissaries and the sekbans ultimately resulted in a rebellion . [ 3 ]
#Text=After the janissaries had been defeated on the Rumelian front , they marched on Istanbul in 1687 to depose Mehmed IV . [ 3 ]
#Text=The latter took actıon to marry his daughter to Yeğen Osman and appointed him to hold the janissaries in check . [ 4 ]
#Text=In 1687 Yeğen Osman was appointed as sanjakbey of the Sanjak of Karahisar-i Sahib in exchange for providing support to the sultan with 5,000 of his men .
#Text=At his insistence , he was also appointed as security chief ( serçeşme ) of this province .

#Text=Instead to bring his forces to the front , by the middle of May 1687 he brought around 4,000 men to Istanbul and instead to defeat forces that threaten the sultan , they actually additionally threaten him . [ 5 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=Only 1,500 of his men were sent to the front at the end of June .
#Text=To satisfy appetites of ambitious Yeğen Osman and win his support
#Text=the sultan made him beylerbey of Rumelia Eyalet with seat in Sofia [ 7 ] and responsible for exceptionally important front toward Holy League .
#Text=Yeğen Osman de facto remained on the position until 1689 and treated the territories he controlled as his personal fiefdom . [ 3 ] [ 8 ]
#Text=He increased taxes to unbearable level to earn as much money as possible for himself , though he regularly denied this when he was faced with criticism . [ 9 ]
#Text=Reign of Suleyman II
#Text=Rebellion
#Text=Mehmed IV to be succeeded by Suleyman II who continued the policy of his predecessor towards sekbans .
#Text=Yeğen Osman , as Rumelian beylerbey , rebelled against new sultan and became the main enemy of the Ottoman government .
#Text=All dissatisfied sekbans gathered around him , including many from Anatolia .
#Text=The sultan offered him the position of serasker of Timișoara , but he refused .

#Text=Sultan appointed him as sanjakbey of the Sanjak of Bosnia and Yeğen 's uncle as sanjakbey of the Sanjak of Herzegovina , but this did not satisfy his ambitions so his forces of 10,000 men continued to plunder the territories under his control , including the Ottoman Serbia and Greece . [ 10 ] [ 11 ]
#Text=According to some sources , Yeğen Osman had more money than Ottoman treasury . [ 11 ]
#Text=In 1688 his forces , notorious because of the robbing of the population , robbed the treasury of Serbian Patriarchate of Peć hidden in Gračanica monastery . [ 12 ] [ 13 ]

#Text=According to one letter written by Catholic bishop Peter Bogdani , Yeğen Osman Pasha threatened to cut off the head of Archbishop of Peć and Serbian Patriarch Arsenije III Crnojević because he received money from Austrians to instigate anti-Ottoman rebellion of Orthodox Serbs . [ 14 ]
#Text=To bring Yeğen Osman to heels
#Text=new sultan appointed Yeğen Osman on the position of governor of Belgrade in 1688 . [ 15 ]
#Text=This appointment angered Yeğen Osman , because this position was subordinated to Ottoman serdar of Hungary , Hasan Pasha .
#Text=He insisted that his new position would not make him subordinated to Ottoman serdar of Hungary , nor porte itself .
#Text=The struggle over position of serdar of Hungary caused deep hatred between Hasan Pasha and Yeğen Osman . [ 16 ]
#Text=When Yeğen Osman went to Belgrade with his forces he forcefully deposed Hasan Pasha by capturing his camp on the Vračar hill and putting him into prison . [ 17 ] [ 16 ]
#Text=Siege of Belgrade 1688
#Text=Siege of Belgrade in 1688
#Text=Main article : Siege of Belgrade ( 1688 )
#Text=When the Holy Roman Empire forces besieged Belgrade in 1688 , the emperor sent a letter to Yeğen Osman and offered him Wallachia to desert Ottomans and switch to their side . [ 17 ]
#Text=Since Yeğen Osman requested all of Slavonia and Bosnia , they did not make an agreement . [ 18 ]
#Text=Austrians positioned ponton bridges near Ostružnica and crossed Sava with 10,000 forces .
#Text=Yeğen Osman attacked them with bulk of his forces , but Austrians repelled his two attacks , captured more land on the right bank of Sava and brought additional forces . [ 19 ]
#Text=When Yeğen Osman realized that his forces were outnumbered , he burned his camp and both Serb populated Belgrade suburbs on Sava and Danube .
#Text=He then retreated to Smederevo where he spent two days looting and burning it .
#Text=Yeğen Osman left Smederevo and went to Niš via Smederevska Palanka . [ 20 ]
#Text=From Niš he wrote to porte reports about the siege and requested military and financial support to defend Belgrade and to annihilate rebellious rayah .
#Text=He explained that Belgrade will fall if his requests would not be met within ten days .
#Text=Porte sent him 120 bags of gold and decided to mobilize Muslim population of Rumelia to deal with rebelled population of Belgrade pashalik . [ 21 ]
#Text=Last years
#Text=Yeğen Osman , by then a Pasha , then attempted to become grand vizier .
#Text=Although Yeğen Osman 's ambition angered the other Ottoman statesmen they were reluctant to make an operation against Yeğen Osman for they were afraid of the exaggerated power of Osman .
#Text=However , in a war council in Edirne , Selim I Giray the Crimean khan and a vassal of the Ottoman Empire called the Ottoman Porte to execute Osman [ 22 ]
#Text=When this happened , the incumbent grand vizier outlawed the sekban corps , threatening soldiers who proved unwilling to disperse with execution , and a civil war ensued . [ 3 ]
#Text=The sekbans gained the upper hand , but a further volte-face of the Ottoman central administration saw Yeğen Osman be captured and executed .

#Text=This did not end the sekban 's rebellions , and while in 1698 the Sultan reached an agreement with the sekbans , extending them guarantees in return for future good behaviour , the agreement was rapidly broken , and sekban 's rebellions continued throughout the 18th century . [ 3 ]
